1. Identify the type of lock on the vehicle. This can be done by looking at the keyhole or door handle.

2. Choose the right tool for the job. There are several tools available in the market that can help you break into a car, such as lock picks, bump keys, and tension wrenches.

3. Practice using these tools on similar locks before attempting to break into a vehicle. This will help you gain confidence and improve your skills.

4. Choose the right location for breaking in. Look for areas where there are no cameras or people around.

5. Use a lock pick or bump key to unlock the door. If the car has an electronic security system, you may need to disable it first using a tension wrench.

6. Once inside the vehicle, make sure to close the door behind you so that no one can see you inside.

7. Be aware of any alarms or other security measures that might alert police or homeowners. If possible, disable these as well.

8. Take only what you need and leave everything else alone. This will help reduce the chance of getting caught.

9. Always clean up after yourself by removing any traces of your presence in the car.
